<Layout title="The Moving Day Checklist for Brisbane Sellers: 8 Weeks Before Settlement to Keys Handed Over | Daniel Gierach Property" description="The period from sale to settlement is dense with administrative tasks. A week-by-week moving day checklist for Brisbane sellers, from 8 weeks out to keys handed over." draft={draft}>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        ← All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 9 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The moving day checklist for Brisbane sellers: 8 weeks before settlement to keys handed over
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Eight weeks sounds long until you start counting. A week-by-week checklist for Brisbane sellers, covering everything from removalist quotes to the keys handed over at settlement.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The contract is signed. The deposit has been paid. The settlement date is six or eight weeks away, and there is a quiet sense that the hard part is done. It is not. The period from sale to settlement is the densest administrative window of the entire process: utility transitions, bank notifications, removalist bookings, packing, cleaning, mail redirection, and the dozens of smaller tasks that tend to surface only when something has been missed.</p>

      <p>A written checklist with weekly milestones is the simplest tool for keeping this period under control. The version below is the one Daniel uses with his own clients: 8 weeks of structured tasks, working from the day the contract is signed through to the keys being handed over and beyond. Adjust the timing for shorter settlements, but keep the structure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">8 weeks before settlement</h2>

      <p>Confirm the settlement date in writing with your solicitor. The contract specifies the settlement date, but check that your solicitor has it correctly recorded and is preparing for that date. Any conditional dates (subject to finance, building and pest) should be confirmed to have passed before you commit to removalist bookings.</p>

      <p>Begin researching removalists. Get three quotes. The Brisbane removalist market varies enormously in quality and price, and the cheapest quote is not always the best value. Ask each removalist about their insurance cover, their access requirements, whether they pack as well as transport, and how they handle delays. A removalist who has handled inner east Brisbane homes regularly is generally a safer choice than one taking the work for the first time.</p>

      <p>Begin sorting belongings into keep, sell, donate, and discard. Eight weeks sounds like plenty of time for this. It is not. The earlier you start, the less stress closer to settlement.</p>

      <p>If buying interstate or in another suburb, intensify the property search. Coordinating sale and purchase settlements is one of the trickiest pieces of timing in real estate. The earlier the next property is identified, the more likely the dates align.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">6 weeks before settlement</h2>

      <p>Book the removalist. Most quality removalists are booked out 4 to 6 weeks ahead during peak periods. Pay any required deposit to secure the date. Confirm their understanding of the pickup address, the destination address, and the access at both ends.</p>

      <p>If you need short-term rental between sale and the next purchase, confirm the dates and the lease. Short-term rentals (typically furnished apartments or houses) book quickly in Brisbane. Coordinating the lease with both the sale settlement and any subsequent purchase needs to happen now, not later.</p>

      <p>Begin notifying institutions of the upcoming address change. Banks, super funds, insurance companies, the ATO, the electoral roll, your private health insurer, your driver's licence and vehicle registration with TMR, and any subscriptions you receive at the address. A spreadsheet of every entity that has your address is the easiest way to keep track. Most institutions accept change-of-address requests dated up to a few weeks in advance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">4 weeks before settlement</h2>

      <p>Arrange utility disconnection at the current address: electricity, gas, internet, phone, and any other services. Most providers require 1 to 2 weeks of notice for disconnection, but booking 4 weeks ahead avoids surprises. The disconnection date should be the day after settlement, not the day of settlement, so that the property remains connected for the final inspection and the buyer's takeover.</p>

      <p>Arrange utility connection at the new address (if relevant). Same notice requirements, same logic. If you are renting short-term, the rental should already include utilities, but verify.</p>

      <p>Schedule mail redirection with Australia Post. Redirection takes effect from a date you specify, so book it for the day after settlement. The standard redirection period is 3 or 6 months. Six months is the safer choice; the small additional cost is worth not missing a piece of mail.</p>

      <p>Begin packing non-essential items. Books, decorative items, out-of-season clothing, garage and shed contents. Anything you will not need in the next four weeks can be packed now. Label every box clearly with both the room of origin and the room of destination.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">2 weeks before settlement</h2>

      <p>Arrange final professional cleaning of the property. Book the cleaner for the day after the furniture is removed (typically the day before settlement). The cleaning standard expected at settlement is "presentation cleaning" rather than a basic clean: kitchens degreased, bathrooms thoroughly cleaned, floors washed, blinds dusted, and the property presented as the buyer last saw it during inspection.</p>

      <p>Schedule the carpet clean for after furniture removal. If there are carpets in the property, professional steam cleaning is usually expected. Book this for the same day as the final clean, after furniture is out.</p>

      <p>Complete utility transition arrangements. Confirm disconnection and connection dates with all providers. Make sure the old account does not auto-pay a final bill that should have been settled.</p>

      <p>Confirm removalist details and access requirements. If the removalist needs to park a large truck on a narrow Brisbane street, the council may require a permit. The removalist will usually arrange this if asked, but do not assume.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">1 week before settlement</h2>

      <p>Confirm with your solicitor that all settlement preparations are on track. The solicitor should be coordinating with the buyer's solicitor and the bank (if a mortgage is being discharged). If you have not heard from your solicitor in the week before settlement, call them.</p>

      <p>Check that all clearances have been obtained. Council rates, water (Urban Utilities in Brisbane), and land tax (if applicable) all require clearances at settlement. Your solicitor manages this, but a quick confirmation prevents last-week surprises.</p>

      <p>Complete packing of all non-essentials. Leave only the items you will need in the final week.</p>

      <p>Check the buyer's pre-settlement inspection date. The buyer is entitled to one inspection in the week before settlement, typically the day before, to confirm that the property is in the same condition as at exchange. Coordinate with the agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The day before settlement</h2>

      <p>The buyer's pre-settlement inspection typically occurs. The agent attends with the buyer. The property should be empty (or at the same state as agreed in the contract) and in the same condition as at exchange. Anything broken, missing, or substantially altered since exchange can become a settlement dispute, so attend to anything that needs attention before the inspection.</p>

      <p>Complete final cleaning. The professional cleaner should be in after the furniture is out. Walk through the property after the cleaner has left and double-check anything they missed.</p>

      <p>Have keys, garage remotes, alarm codes, and instruction manuals ready for handover. Keys: front door, back door, gates, sheds, garage, mailbox. Remotes: garage door, gates, alarm. Codes: alarm, smart locks, any internet-connected devices the new owner will need to access. Manuals: appliances, pool, irrigation, anything mechanical that the buyer will need to operate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement day</h2>

      <p>Your solicitor confirms settlement has occurred. In Queensland, settlements are now mostly completed electronically through PEXA, so the actual settlement event takes place at a time agreed between the solicitors. You receive confirmation, usually by email, when settlement is complete.</p>

      <p>Release keys and remotes to the agent for handover to the buyer. The agent typically meets the buyer at the property at a time arranged with both parties. Do not release keys before settlement is confirmed.</p>

      <p>Take final meter readings if not already done by the utility providers. A photo of the meter on the day of settlement is a simple way to settle any disputes about final bills.</p>

      <p>Photograph the empty, cleaned property. A simple set of photos protects you if there is any later dispute about the condition the property was left in.</p>

      <p>Leave the property no later than the settlement time specified in the contract. Once settlement has been confirmed, the property belongs to the buyer. Continued occupation, even by a few hours, can become a legal issue.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">After settlement</h2>

      <p>The agent's commission is paid from the settlement proceeds. Your solicitor handles this; you do not need to pay the agent separately.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor provides the settlement statement showing all financial movements. Sale price, deposit applied, agent's commission, solicitor's fees, council and water clearances, mortgage discharged (if any), and the net proceeds paid to you. Review this statement carefully and keep a copy for your records and your tax return.</p>

      <p>Your mortgage (if any) is discharged. The bank releases its security on the property and provides confirmation. This is automatic if your solicitor and the bank have done their work properly, but check that you receive the confirmation.</p>

      <p>You receive the net proceeds. These are typically paid into the bank account nominated in the settlement instructions, the same day as settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common mistakes to avoid</h2>

      <p>Leaving disconnection arrangements until the last minute. Many providers require 1 to 2 weeks of notice. A panicked call the day before settlement is too late.</p>

      <p>Leaving belongings at the property after settlement. Even small items left behind (a piece of furniture in the garage, garden tools in the shed, items stored in a roof cavity) can become a dispute with the new owner. The property should be empty at settlement unless the contract specifically allows otherwise.</p>

      <p>Forgetting the spare keys, garage remotes, and alarm codes. The buyer needs every key and every remote that exists for the property. A single missing key, discovered after settlement, is a small inconvenience that can sour the early relationship with the new owner.</p>

      <p>Not photographing the property at settlement. Disputes about condition are rare, but they happen. A simple set of photos protects you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to forget</h2>

      <p>All keys: front door, back door, gates, cars (if any vehicles are being sold with the property), sheds, garage, mailbox, body corporate facility keys (gym, pool, BBQ area, mail room).</p>

      <p>All remotes: garage door, automatic gates, alarm system, anything else that is operated remotely.</p>

      <p>Alarm codes and operating manuals: the buyer needs to be able to disarm the alarm immediately on taking possession.</p>

      <p>Appliance manuals and warranty documents: dishwasher, oven, cooktop, rangehood, washing machine, dryer, fridge if included, air conditioning. The buyer is entitled to whatever warranties remain on these items.</p>

      <p>Pool maintenance schedule and chemicals: if the property has a pool, leaving the maintenance schedule, chemical inventory, and contact details for the pool service provider is a courtesy that the new owner will appreciate.</p>

      <p>Any keys or instructions for body corporate facilities: if the property is in a unit complex, the body corporate facility keys, the resident manager's contact details, and the by-laws are useful to leave with the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Eight weeks may sound long, but it disappears quickly once you start counting actual tasks. A written checklist with weekly milestones prevents last-minute panic and keeps the period from sale to settlement under control.</p>

      <p>Review the checklist with your solicitor and your agent. They have done this hundreds of times and can flag anything you missed. The cost of a five-minute conversation is nothing compared to the cost of missing a clearance, a notification, or a key on the day of settlement.</p>

      <p>Settlement should be the culmination of a sale that has been managed well, not the moment when everything goes wrong. With the right preparation, it is.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
